Here is a Julia solution for your problem. It first checks if the input `temps` list is not empty and then computes average, maximum, minimum temperatures using `Statistics` package functions. After that, it checks whether the sequence of daily temperature data has an increasing trend or decreasing one or neither based on the differences between successive temperatures.

```julia
using Statistics

function weather_data_analyzer(temps)
    if isempty(temps)
        return (average = nothing, max = nothing, min = nothing, trend = nothing)
    else
        avg_temp = mean(temps)
        max_temp = maximum(temps)
        min_temp = minimum(temps)

        if length(temps) == 1
            return (average = avg_temp, max = max_temp, min = min_temp, trend = :stable)
        else
            diffs = diff(temps)

            if all(x -> x > 0, diffs)
                return (average = avg_temp, max = max_temp, min = min_temp, trend = :increasing)
            elseif all(x -> x < 0, diffs)
                return (average = avg_temp, max = max_temp, min = min_temp, trend = :decreasing)
            else
                return (average = avg_temp, max = max_temp, min = min_temp, trend = :stable)
            end
        end
    end
end
```
This function uses `mean`, `maximum` and `minimum` functions from Statistics package to compute average, maximum and minimum temperatures. Then it checks if the sequence of daily temperature data has an increasing or decreasing trend based on the differences between successive temperatures.
